🔄 What Is Token Rotation in JWT?

Token rotation (more precisely refresh token rotation) means:

Every time a refresh token is used to get a new access token, the server also issues a new refresh token and invalidates the old one.

So refresh tokens are one-time use.

🧠 Why Rotation Is Needed

With plain JWT setup:

Access token → short-lived (e.g., 15 min)

Refresh token → long-lived (e.g., 7 days)

If attacker steals refresh token:

Attacker can keep generating new access tokens
until refresh token expires.

That’s dangerous.

Rotation solves this.

🚀 How Token Rotation Works (Step-by-Step)

Let’s use JSON Web Token conceptually.

🟢 Step 1 — Login

Server issues:

Access Token A1 (15 min)
Refresh Token R1 (7 days)

Server stores R1 in database.

🟢 Step 2 — Access Token Expires

Client sends:

POST /refresh
refresh_token = R1

Server checks:

Is R1 valid?

Is it revoked?

Is it expired?

If valid:

Server responds with:

Access Token A2
Refresh Token R2

And then:

R1 → marked as revoked
R2 → stored in DB

Now R1 can never be used again.

🔥 What Happens If Token Is Stolen?

Imagine attacker stole R1.

Two possibilities:

Case 1️⃣ Legit user refreshes first

User uses R1 → gets R2
R1 is revoked.

Attacker tries using R1:

❌ Server sees R1 already used
❌ Detects token reuse
❌ Can revoke all sessions
❌ Force re-login

Attack stopped.

Case 2️⃣ Attacker uses R1 first

Attacker gets R2
R1 revoked.

Later, real user tries R1:

❌ Reuse detected
❌ System knows something is wrong
❌ Revoke entire session

Again — breach detected.

🎯 That’s the Key Benefit

Rotation turns refresh token theft from:

Silent long-term compromise

into:

Detectable security event

🧱 Why This Adds State

Access tokens → stateless
Refresh tokens → stored in DB

Rotation requires storing:

Token ID (jti)

Expiry

Revoked status

Parent token (optional)

So refresh tokens are usually:

Stored hashed in DB

Not purely stateless

🏗 Visual Flow

Without rotation:

R1 → R1 → R1 → R1 (reusable)

With rotation:

R1 → R2 → R3 → R4
(each one invalidates previous)

Chain-based trust model.

⚠️ Important Detail

Many secure systems also implement:

Refresh Token Reuse Detection

If a revoked token is used again:

→ Immediately revoke entire session chain.

Very powerful protection.

🏁 Final Definition

Token rotation means:

Every refresh token can be used only once.
Using it issues a new refresh token and invalidates the old one.

It prevents silent long-term session hijacking.

